lace rxn_011 with a more plausible cyanamide source (e.g., from CaCN2 mineral weathering or separate photochemical pathway)\", \"Provide experimental or mechanistic justification for rxn_016; currently this is a significant gap\", \"Consider whether 2-aminoimidazole contributes to histidine synthesis at all or is better suited for nucleotide activation\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.85,\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.70,\n        \"rxn_013\": 0.85,\n        \"rxn_014\": 0.80,\n        \"rxn_017\": 0.48,\n        \"rxn_018\": 0.88,\n        \"rxn_019\": 0.90\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.68,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.72,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.78,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.70,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.71,\n      \"feedback\": \"The purine-linked HCN oligomerization route is attractive in principle, connecting histidine synthesis to purine metabolism as suggested by the literature. The HCN tetramerization to DAMN (rxn_013) and DAMN photorearrangement to AIC (rxn_014) are well-documented. However, rxn_017 (AIC + formaldehyde \u2192 imidazole-4-acetaldehyde) is highly speculative. This requires simultaneous decarboxylation of the carboxamide, deamination, and C-C bond formation\u2014a transformation without experimental precedent in this context. The biological pathway uses AICAR ribotide in a complex enzymatic sequence, not a simple mineral-catalyzed step.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_017\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Detail the mechanism for AIC \u2192 imidazole-4-acetaldehyde conversion\", \"Consider whether an AICAR-like intermediate with a sugar moiety would be needed\", \"This step may require multiple sub-reactions to be plausible\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_001\": 0.90,\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.72,\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.85,\n        \"rx